Data: sequence in a small collection of unphased

High throughput sequencing has greatly improved our ability to
demographic models. A popular approach for inferring
parameters in these demographic models is by sampling
genealogical histories at many short unlinked loci using a Markov
chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm, e.g., IMa (Hey and
en, 2007), BP&P (Yang and Rannala, 2010), and G
(Gronau et al, 2011). The use of explicit coalescent models by
these methods makes them powerful for inferring demographic
parameters, but they are limited in their ability to assess the fit of
rred model to data. We propose a novel and flexible
statistical measure for model fit that is based on Bayes factors
estimated using the samples generated by the MCMC algorithm.
This method takes advantage of the strength of existing
ethods in exploring the space of
plausible genealogies, and can be implemented through very
minor adjustments to the existing source code and no
modifications to the sampling algorithm itself.
